Synchronous programming is when code is executed one line at a time, and the next line cannot be executed until the previous line has finished running. This means that if there is a long-running task, such as fetching data from a server or performing a complex calculation, it will block the execution of other code until it is complete.
For example:

```javascript
function syncExample() {
 console.log('Line 1');
 // This line will wait for the previous line to finish running before executing
 console.log('Line 2');
}

syncExample();
```

Asynchronous programming, on the other hand, allows code to be executed out of order, so that long-running tasks do not block the execution of other code. Instead, these tasks are put into a queue and run in the background while other code continues to execute.
For example:

```javascript
function asyncExample() {
 setTimeout(() => {
 console.log('Line 2');
 }, 1000);
 console.log('Line 1');
}

asyncExample();
```

In this example, the `setTimeout` function is used to delay the execution of the second line for one second, allowing the first line to execute immediately. This demonstrates how asynchronous programming can be used to perform long-running tasks in the background without blocking other code.

